Would you like me to insert it directly into your uploaded ODB form PDF and give you the final file (with the text already placed), or do you prefer keeping it as plain text for manual insertion?', 'ODB', 'Vahid', '+989123379445', 'Full-Time', 'seraj.m', 2.0, 'Post-Flight and Pre-Next Flight Preparation (Cockpit Crew) updated', 'TEHR', 1.0, NULL, 2.0, 10030.0, '', 'Bozorgnia');
INSERT INTO `report_45_2025_08_08` (`DaysUnAcknowledged`, `EmailAddress`, `RequiresAction`, `BaseName`, `URL`, `DeleteOnAck`, `AlertStatusName`, `ModifiedAt`, `CreatedAt`, `PersonnelID`, `DepartmentName`, `PhoneNo`, `AlertBody`, `AlertCategoryName`, `FirstName`, `MobileNo`, `EmploymentText`, `CreatedBy`, `DepartmentID`, `AlertTitle`, `BaseShortName`, `AlertStatus`, `ModifiedBy`, `BaseID`, `AlertID`, `FaxNo`, `LastName`) VALUES (53, 'Bozorgnia.v@Raimonairways.ir;Bozorgnia.v@Raimonairways.net', 0, 'Tehran', '~/Controls/GetFile.ashx?Type=Document&ID=15129', 0, 'Critical', NULL, '2025-08-23T16:40:06.173', 34.0, 'Pilot', '', 'Action required:
1. Responsibility for Submission
•	The pilot-in-command (PIC) is ultimately responsible for ensuring that an ATS Flight Plan is submitted when required.
•	In commercial operations, the ATS FPL may be submitted on behalf of the PIC by the operator, Operations Control Centre (OCC), or a designated flight dispatcher.
•	The latest valid flight plan submitted by the PIC, operator, or representative is the plan used by ATS units.
2. Time of Submission
•	Within Tehran FIR, ATS Flight Plans shall be submitted:
• Not more than 120 hours (5 days) before the Estimated Off-Block Time (EOBT).
• Not less than 60 minutes before the EOBT.
•	Exceptions:
• Repetitive Flight Plans (RPLs).
• Special flights requiring authorization.
•	If a flight plan is filed more than 24 hours before EOBT, the Date of Flight (DOF) must be inserted in Item 18 of the flight plan.
3. Place of Submission
a) Preferably at the Air Traffic Services Reporting Office (ARO) at the departure aerodrome.
b) If no ARO is available, the flight plan shall be submitted to the appropriate ATS unit by AFTN, fax, or other approved means.
4. Validity of the Flight Plan
•	An ATS Flight Plan is valid for:
• 30 minutes after EOBT if any portion of the flight is operated under IFR.
• 60 minutes after EOBT if operated entirely under VFR.
•	De-icing operations: validity may be extended, subject to ATS coordination.
•	Delays exceeding 75 minutes: require coordination between operator and ATS units.
5. Delay, Modification, and Cancellation
•	Permitted revision: Only one revision is acceptable up to:
• 30 minutes after EOBT for IFR flights.
• 60 minutes after EOBT for VFR flights.
•	Revisions are effective 10 minutes after reception by ATS via AFTN. If submitted by fax or phone, they must be recordable and acknowledged.
•	Cases requiring revision:
a) A delay of 30 minutes (IFR) / 60 minutes (VFR) beyond EOBT.
b) Change in aircraft type and/or registration mark (if registration not used as Item 7: ACFT IDENT).
Notes:
1.	Revisions must be received by ATS units prior to aircraft start-up request.
2.	If both delay and aircraft type/registration change occur, a CHG (Change) message must be issued.
3.	If aircraft type/registration change affects other fields of the FPL, the modification must be transmitted in full detail.
4.	If the day of flight changes past 0000 UTC, a CHG message must replace a DLA (Delay) message, indicating both EOBT and DOF.
5.	If departure aerodrome, destination aerodrome, route, or aircraft identification changes, the filed FPL (or RPL) is cancelled and a new FPL must be submitted.
6. When a Change is Required (General Rules)
Changes must be submitted whenever there is a significant deviation from the originally filed FPL, including:
•	Change in route or flight rules (e.g., IFR ? VFR).
•	Change in level (altitude/FL) outside tolerance (±300 ft in IFR RVSM, ±400 ft in VFR).
•	EOBT delay beyond 30 minutes (IFR) or 60 minutes (VFR).
•	Change of destination or alternate aerodrome.
•	Change in aircraft type or registration mark.
•	Change in endurance or total persons on board (safety data).
•	Change in SSR transponder capability or COM/NAV equipment.
•	PIC name:
• If the FPL was submitted and signed by PIC ? name must match.
• If the FPL was submitted by OCC/dispatcher on behalf of the operator ? change of PIC name is not required.
', 'ODB', 'Vahid', '+989123379445', 'Full-Time', 'seraj.m', 2.0, 'ATS Flight Plan (ATS FPL) – Filing, Validity, and Revisions updated', 'TEHR', 1.0, NULL, 2.0, 10031.0, '', 'Bozorgnia');
INSERT INTO `report_45_2025_08_08` (`DaysUnAcknowledged`, `EmailAddress`, `RequiresAction`, `BaseName`, `URL`, `DeleteOnAck`, `AlertStatusName`, `ModifiedAt`, `CreatedAt`, `PersonnelID`, `DepartmentName`, `PhoneNo`, `AlertBody`, `AlertCategoryName`, `FirstName`, `MobileNo`, `EmploymentText`, `CreatedBy`, `DepartmentID`, `AlertTitle`, `BaseShortName`, `AlertStatus`, `ModifiedBy`, `BaseID`, `AlertID`, `FaxNo`, `LastName`) VALUES (53, 'Bozorgnia.v@Raimonairways.ir;Bozorgnia.v@Raimonairways.net', 0, 'Tehran', '~/Controls/GetFile.ashx?Type=Document&ID=15130', 0, 'Critical', NULL, '2025-08-23T16:50:09.063', 34.0, 'Pilot', '', 'Action required:
1. General Requirement
RAIMON Airways selects at least one destination alternate aerodrome for each IFR flight unless the destination aerodrome is isolated or both conditions apply:
a) Flight time from take-off to landing does not exceed 6 hours; and
b) Two separate usable runways are available at the destination, and weather forecasts for 1 hour before until 1 hour after ETA show:
• Ceiling = 2 000 ft or circling height + 500 ft (whichever higher).
• Visibility = 5 km.
c) 500 lbs operational extra fuel must be considered when planning with only one destination alternate.
2. Two Destination Alternates Required
RAIMON Airways selects two alternates when:
•	Destination weather forecast (±1 hr of ETA) is below planning minima; or
•	No meteorological information is available.
3. Criteria for Selection of Destination Alternate
•	Runway, taxiway, and parking characteristics.
•	Availability of navigation/approach aids.
•	ATS, MET, firefighting, customs, immigration, and other services.
•	Distance from destination aerodrome.
•	Passenger protection possibility.
•	Availability of JET A1 fuel.
•	Passenger handling and aircraft technical assistance.


4. Planning Minima for Destination Alternate
Type of Approach	Ceiling (Cloud Base/Vertical Visibility)	RVR/VIS
Type B instrument approach	DA/H + 200 ft	RVR/VIS + 800 m
Type A instrument approach	DA/H or MDA/H + 400 ft	RVR/VIS + 1 500 m
Circling	MDA/H + 400 ft	VIS + 1 500 m
5. Notes on Instrument Approaches
•	Type A: Circling-only minima (e.g., VOR-A, NDB-A, RNAV(GNSS)-A). Pilot must circle visually after reaching MDA/H.
•	Type B: Straight-in landing minima (e.g., ILS, LOC RWY, RNAV RWY). Published DA/H or MDA/H applies. Circling minima may also be published.
•	Circling: Visual maneuver after an instrument approach to land on another runway due to wind/obstacle/runway alignment.
6. No Destination Alternate Required When:
•	Flight duration = 6 hrs; and
•	Two usable separate runways exist with forecasts showing ceiling = 2 000 ft or circling height + 500 ft, and visibility = 5 km; or
•	Destination is isolated.
Runway Consideration: Runways at the same aerodrome count as “separate” if:
•	They are independent landing surfaces;
•	One runway blocked does not affect the other; and
•	Each has its own published approach procedure.
7. Number of Alternates Required
•	At least one alternate for each IFR flight.
•	Two alternates when:
• Weather at destination (±1 hr ETA) below planning minima; or
• No MET info available.
•	All required alternates must be specified in the Operational Flight Plan (OFP).
', 'ODB', 'Vahid', '+989123379445', 'Full-Time', 'seraj.m', 2.0, 'Destination Alternate (DEST ALTN) – CAT.OP.MPA.180 updated', 'TEHR', 1.0, NULL, 2.0, 10032.0, '', 'Bozorgnia');
